text: If anyone receives an error like this "ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'pycocotools'"   Do the following 1. git clone https://github.com/pdollar/coco.git 2. cd coco/PythonAPI  3. open MakeFile and change "python" command to "python3" command. Save makefile 4. make  5. sudo make install 6. sudo python setup.py install   Note: Make sure you have cython installed

author: @ohaRega
text: Extra info for curious viewers who are on Linux: "Someone tell me why I need to use this export command even though I never rebooted." It's because the modification on PYTHONPATH via the export command only persists while the current Terminal instance is running. In other words, you need to modify the PYTHONPATH every time you open up a new Terminal. A way around this is to add the export command to the end of the ~/.bashrc file (which is a script that runs at each Terminal startup).

author: @darshild5853
text: IMPORT ERROR If you're on windows and getting a "no module called nets" or some import error make sure to do the following:  Go to System -> Advanced system settings -> Environment Variables -> System Variables -> New, and add a variable with the name PYTHONPATH and these values (make sure the path matches these are just examples): C:\Program Files\Python36\  OR anaconda if you're using that C:\TensorFlow\models C:\TensorFlow\models\research C:\TensorFlow\models\research\slim C:\TensorFlow\models\research\object_detection  Then while still there, in the system variables section click on path and add this  => " %PYTHONPATH% " (not the quotes)  => AND THEN REBOOT YOUR PC  TRAIN.PY train.py is in ...models\research\object_detection\legacy so I ran this from ...models\research\object_detection instead:  python legacy/train.py --logtostderr --train_dir=training/ --pipeline_config_path=training/ssd_mobilenet_v1_pets.config

author: @ahmedhany2994
text: for anyone who meet the problem :  No module named 'object_detection' or can't find train.py because, now it exists in legacy.   u can use model_main.py instead of it   but, if u insist of using train.py xD  instead of tweaking things & all that kind of stuff,  the solution is very simple. author: @Kingsizeshrimp
text: @sentdex UPDATE, from 1.august 2018: The architecture of the folders have totally changed when downloading tensorflow/models. Therefore I found a fix. go into: "https://github.com/datitran/object_detector_app". download/clone the "object_detection"-folder and replace with the the current "object_detection" folder you have in your tensorflow/models/research/. Then after this, do the step shown in 9:42 where you paste your object-detection files into "object_detection". Make sure your ssd_mobilenet_v1_pets.config file has right addresses in terms of /data and /training folder. If you have trouble, put everything in except ssd_mobilenet_v1_pets.config into your /data folder  then repeat the steps: # From tensorflow/models/research protoc object_detection/protos/*.proto --python_out=.  # From tensorflow/models/research export PYTHONPATH=$PYTHONPATH:`pwd`:`pwd`/slim  # From tensorflow/models/research sudo python3 setup.py install  NOW:  # From tensorflow/models/research/object_detection python3 train.py --logtostderr --train_dir=training/ --pipeline_config_path=training/ssd_mobilenet_v1_pets.config  Here you will get errors Mention of Python 3: AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'iteritems' for "python ./object_detection/builders/model_builder_test.py"  to solve this, check this link: https://github.com/tensorflow/models/issues/1587. You have to change from .iteritems to .items. You will have to repeat this for several files, including: batcher.py, prefetcher.py in the objectdetection/core-folder  Also do the same for ops.py in the object_detection/utils folder  THEN:  # From tensorflow/models/research/object_detection python3 train.py --logtostderr --train_dir=training/ --pipeline_config_path=training/ssd_mobilenet_v1_pets.config  YOU'RE WELCOME

author: @SalmanGhauri
text: Hey there, a bit late but anyways, the export command (setting an environment variable and it to path in your case) in bash works only for existing session, if you want to make it persistent (available globally) you should add it to ~/.bashrc and restart the terminals session.  Its like when you use absolute path for pip or any other program from windows CMD which you can make global by adding it to PATH.

author: @Johnnyboycurtis
text: For anyone who is curious, on https://youtu.be/JR8CmWyh2E8?t=12m4s he runs into some trouble because if you run `echo $PYTHONPATH` it may return blank, or without the needed directories appended to it. Python only knows to look for modules in directories where it's currently located at or in directories specified by PYTHONPATH. The command   # From tensorflow/models/research/ export PYTHONPATH=$PYTHONPATH:`pwd`:`pwd`/slim  specifies that you should run this in the directory where all your files are located in. From there, the command will append the current directory path and the slim directory. So if you run `echo $PYTHONPATH` afterwards, you should see new paths added.

text: exports sets a temporary environment variable for the current session. if you close the console, or start a new instance of bash you get a new set of environment variables for that. you can make it fake-permanent if you include the export function in .bashrc then every time you open bash, it is automatically exported.

author: @roar779
text: If you're on Linux, instead of copying the files into models directory (9:43), you can do the steps below:  1) Add these lines at the end of your ~/.bashrc file:          export MODELS= path_to_models_directory (in this case it's ~/Desktop/models)     export PYTHONPATH=$MODELS:$MODELS/slim     export OBJ_DET=$MODELS/object_detection         Note that the paths you specify here should NOT end with "/".     The second line gets rid of the need to export every time you open a new terminal.       2) Run this from the terminal and close all your opened terminals. This way that file gets updated without the need for a reboot.      source ~/.bashrc           3) cd into the directory where your "training","data",etc. folders are (in this tutorial it's ~/Desktop/object-detection/)  4) From there instead of python3 train.py in (11:47), run this: python3 $OBJ_DET/train.py  5) If you want to test your trained model without copying the files into the models directory, do the above steps and see my comment on the next tutorial.
